ial objects and more theoretical interventions. Among the book's highlights are a foundational treatment of the second commandment by Jan Assmann; an essay by W.J.T. Mitchell on Nicolas Poussin that will be a model for future discussions of art objects; a groundbreaking consideration of the Islamic ban on images by Mika Natif; and a lucid description by Jean-Luc Marion of his cutting-edge phenomenology of the visible.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aArt and religion. 0aIdolatry in art. 0aIdolatry in literature. 0aIdolatry. 0aIdols and images in art. 0aIdols and images in literature. 0aIdols and imagesxWorship. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh1 aEllenbogen, Josh, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTugendhaft, Aaron, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478181740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804781817423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804781817.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles